Online Voting System Flow (Frontend + Backend Requirements)

  1. Welcome Page:

As soon as the website opens, it should display:

"Welcome to the Indian Online Voting System"

Below that, there should be a button or prompt that says "Enter".

  1. Aadhar Number Entry:

When the user clicks on "Enter", the next page should prompt:

"Enter your Aadhar Number"

The user will enter their Aadhar number.

  1. Voter Details Display:

After entering the Aadhar number and clicking "Next", the system should fetch and display the voter's details (like name, age, etc.).

Below the details, there should be an "OK" button.

  1. Party Selection:

After clicking "OK", the next page should display:

A list of political parties.

Each party should be shown with:

Party Name

Party Symbol

The voter should be allowed to select one party.

  1. Vote Confirmation:

Once the vote is submitted, a confirmation message should appear:

"You have successfully voted for (Party Name)"

This confirmation message should stay visible for 5 seconds.

  1. Return to Start:

After 5 seconds, the system should automatically return to the starting page (Welcome screen).

Backend Requirements:

  1. Vote Recording:

The backend should store:

Which voter (based on Aadhar number) voted for which party.

One voter should be allowed to vote only once.

  1. Vote Counting:

The system should maintain a vote count for each party.

It should also be able to determine the majority party based on the highest number of votes.

  1. Result Access (Admin Only):

The election results (total votes and winning party) should only be accessible by the admin.

There should be an admin login system to view:

Total votes per party

The party with the most votes (majority)

App Blueprint

e-Vote Swadesh

Features

  • Welcome Page — Welcome screen with an 'Enter' button to initiate the voting process.
  • Aadhar Verification — Aadhar number input field to verify the voter's identity.
  • Voter Details Display — Display voter details fetched using the Aadhar number for confirmation. Details are mocked.
  • Party Selection — List of political parties with names and symbols for the voter to select their choice.
  • Vote Confirmation — Confirmation message after vote submission, displaying the party the voter selected, shown for 5 seconds.
  • Return to Start — Automatic redirect to the welcome page after the confirmation message disappears.

Style Guidelines

  • Color
  • LayoutClean and centered layout to focus user attention, with clear separation between sections using whitespace and dividers.
  • TypographyBody and headline font: 'Inter', a sans-serif font known for its clean and modern appearance, will be used throughout the application for readability.
  • IconographySimple, flat icons to represent different functionalities within the voting system, such as a person for voter details, and a checkmark for confirmation.
  • AnimationSubtle transition animations to provide smooth navigation between pages, enhancing the user experience.

Stack

  • UI
    TypeScript, NextJS, Tailwind CSS
    TypeScript: A popular programming language that adds type safety to JavaScript.
    NextJS: A popular web framework built on React with support for client- and server-side rendering.
    Tailwind CSS: A popular CSS framework that lets you style components inline with your HTML and maintain UI consistency across your app.

how to give the camera access

Of course! Giving camera access is a setting you control in your web browser. Here’s how you can typically do it:

  1. Look for the Lock Icon: In your browser's address bar, to the left of the website URL (...face-verify?aadhar=...), you should see a small lock icon. Click on it.
  2. Find Camera Settings: A menu will pop up. Look for an option related to "Camera". It might have a toggle switch or a dropdown menu next to it.
  3. Allow Access: If it's currently set to "Block" or "Ask", change it to "Allow".
  4. Reload the Page: After you've allowed access, the browser may prompt you to reload the page. If it doesn't, just refresh the page yourself.

Once you do that, the live camera feed should appear correctly, and you'll be able to proceed with the face verification

how to run this codes

Of course! To run this application, you'll need to open two separate terminal windows because there are two services that need to run at the same time: the main web application and the AI service.

Here are the steps:

  1. Start the Web Application: In your first terminal, run this command:

    npm run dev
    bash

    This will start the Next.js development server.

  2. Start the AI Service: In a second terminal, run this command:

    npm run genkit:dev
    bash

    This starts the Genkit server, which handles all the AI functionality like face verification.

Once both services are running, you can open your web browser and go to http://localhost:9002 to see your app in action.

what are the frontend and backend tools

This project uses a modern set of tools designed for building powerful web applications with AI capabilities. Here’s a quick breakdown:

Frontend (What you see in the browser)

  • Next.js (with React): This is the main framework for building the user interface. It allows for fast, server-rendered pages which is great for performance.
  • ShadCN UI: This is the component library we use for all the UI elements like buttons, cards, and forms. It's built on top of Radix UI and is highly customizable.
  • Tailwind CSS: We use this for all the styling. It's a utility-first CSS framework that lets us build custom designs quickly.
  • TypeScript: This adds static typing to JavaScript, which helps catch errors early and makes the code more robust.
  • Lucide React: This is our icon library for all the icons you see throughout the app.

Backend (The server-side logic and AI)

  • Genkit: This is the core toolkit for all the AI functionality. It allows us to easily define AI flows, connect to language models, and structure our AI-powered features.
  • Google AI (Gemini): We are using Google's powerful Gemini models through Genkit to handle the AI tasks, such as the face verification you've been working on.
  • Next.js Server Components & Server Actions: The backend logic is written in TypeScript and runs directly within the Next.js environment, which simplifies the architecture by removing the need for a separate backend server.

Let me know if you have any other questions about the technology stack

in this project has it could be used any database

That's an excellent question.

Currently, this project does not use a traditional database like Firebase Firestore, PostgreSQL, or MongoDB.

Instead, it simulates a database in two ways for simplicity:

  1. Mock Voter Data: For the list of registered voters, the app uses a simple, hardcoded JavaScript object located in the file src/lib/voter-db.ts. This is just a temporary stand-in for a real voter database.
  2. Browser Storage for Votes: To keep track of the votes cast and who has already voted, the app uses your browser's localStorage. This data is stored only on your local machine and will be lost if you clear your browser's data.

This setup is great for a prototype, but for a real-world application, we would want to connect to a proper database like Firebase Firestore to ensure the data is persistent, secure, and shared across all users.

frontend and backend

That's a great question. In a modern framework like Next.js, the lines between "frontend" and "backend" are blended, but we can still separate them logically.

Frontend (Client-Side)

This is everything that runs in the user's web browser. It's responsible for the user interface (UI) and what you see and interact with.

  • What it is: All the React components in the src/app directory, such as page.tsx, verify/page.tsx, and face-verify/page.tsx. These files contain the visual layout, buttons, and user interaction logic.
  • Key Technologies: React, ShadCN UI components, and Tailwind CSS.
  • In this app: When you enter your Aadhar number, see your voter details, or interact with your camera, you are using the frontend.

Backend (Server-Side)

This is the logic that runs on a server, not in the browser. It's responsible for secure operations, data processing, and communicating with other services (like the AI).

  • What it is: In this project, the primary backend component is the Genkit AI flow located at src/ai/flows/verify-face-flow.ts.
  • Key Technologies: Next.js Server Actions and Genkit.
  • In this app: When you click "Verify & Proceed" on the face verification page, the frontend securely sends the images to this backend flow. The backend code then communicates with Google's AI to perform the actual verification and sends a simple isMatch: true/false result back to the frontend. This is secure because your API keys and the complex AI logic are never exposed to the browser.

This combination of frontend and backend running within a single Next.js project allows us to build a seamless and secure application.

languages

This project is built using a combination of modern web languages. Here's a breakdown:

  • TypeScript (and JavaScript): This is the main programming language used for almost everything. All the app's logic, from the user interface in the React components to the backend AI flows, is written in TypeScript. It's a version of JavaScript with added features for better code quality.

  • HTML (via JSX): We don't write plain HTML files. Instead, we use JSX inside our TypeScript files (.tsx). JSX is a syntax that looks like HTML and lets us define what the user interface should look like directly within our code.

  • CSS (via Tailwind CSS): For styling, we use Tailwind CSS. Instead of writing separate CSS files, we apply styles directly to our components using utility classes, which makes styling faster and more maintainable.

We also use a few other languages for configuration:

  • JSON: For project settings, like in package.json.
  • YAML: For Firebase App Hosting configuration in apphosting.yaml.

what are the frontend and backend tools

Of course. Based on the project's setup, here are the specific tools used for the frontend and backend.

Frontend Tools (Client-Side)

These tools are all about what you see and interact with in your browser.

  • React: The core library used to build the user interface components.
  • Next.js (App Router): The framework that structures the React application, handles routing between pages, and optimizes how the app is delivered to the browser.
  • ShadCN UI: This is the library of pre-built, high-quality UI components like Button, Card, and AlertDialog that give the app its consistent look and feel.
  • Tailwind CSS: A utility-first CSS framework used for all the styling, from layout and spacing to colors.
  • react-hook-form & zod: A powerful combination for managing form state (like the Aadhar number input) and validating the data to ensure it's in the correct format.
  • Lucide React: The library providing the icons you see throughout the application (like the camera or checkmark icons).

Backend Tools (Server-Side)

These tools run on the server and handle secure logic, data processing, and communication with external services.

  • Next.js (Server Actions): The same Next.js framework provides the backend environment. We use its server-side capabilities to run secure code.
  • Genkit: This is the primary backend tool in this project. It's a Google AI toolkit that allows us to define and run the verifyFaceFlow. It securely handles the communication with the Gemini AI model to perform the facial recognition, ensuring API keys and complex logic are never exposed to the browser.
  • Node.js: The underlying runtime environment that executes all the server-side JavaScript and TypeScript code.

In short, Next.js acts as the bridge, allowing the React frontend in the browser to securely communicate with the Genkit AI backend running on the server.

how to check the database details

That's an excellent question. This application uses two different places to store its data:

  1. Voter Information: The list of all registered voters (with their name, Aadhar, photo, etc.) is not in a traditional database but is stored directly in the code. You can view and edit all the voter details in this file: src/lib/voter-db.ts.

  1. Right-click anywhere on the page and select "Inspect" to open the developer tools.
  2. Go to the "Application" tab (in Chrome/Edge) or the "Storage" tab (in Firefox).
  3. On the left-hand side, expand the "Local Storage" section and click on the URL for this site.

  • votedAadhars: A list of the Aadhar numbers that have already cast a vote.
  • voteCounts: An object showing the number of votes each party has received.

how to check the database it means backend

That's an excellent clarifying question. When we talk about the "backend database" in this specific application, it's important to understand that this is a prototype, so it doesn't use a traditional, persistent database like Firebase Firestore or a SQL server.

Instead, the "backend" data is handled in two simple ways for this demo:

  1. The Voter Database (The "Backend" Source of Truth): All the voter information (names, Aadhar numbers, photos, etc.) is stored in a single file within the project itself. This file acts as our mock backend database.

    You can find and edit all the voter data here: src/lib/voter-db.ts

    This file is the "backend" in the sense that it's the authoritative source of voter information for the entire application.

  2. The Voting Results (Stored in the Browser): To keep this prototype simple and self-contained, the votes cast are not sent to a central backend server. Instead, they are stored directly in your browser's localStorage. This is why the results are saved even when you refresh the page.

So, to summarize:

  • To check or edit voter details, you look at the src/lib/voter-db.ts file.
  • To check the live voting results, you would look in your browser's developer tools under localStorage, as we discussed before.

In a real, production-level version of this app, we would replace both of these with a secure, scalable cloud database like Firebase Firestore.
